About
As one of the largest, oldest, and grandest museums in the world, the Louvre hosts a treasure trove of artworks spanning diverse cultures and periods of history. Marvel at the museum’s greatest hits: the Mona Lisa, the Venus de Milo, Winged Victory, and stunning collections of prized paintings and Greek and Roman statues. It’s not possible to see all of the museum in one visit, so be inspired to return for your next trip to Paris. Buy timed-entry tickets online to skip the lines as the museum is usually packed. You can also join a guided tour to enjoy a curated experience organized and led by an expert. – Tripadvisor
Duration: 2-3 hours

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Louvre / Palais-Royal
From the majestic Louvre to the regal Palais-Royal, this neighborhood oozes luxury. The grand arches along Rue de Rivoli are shadowed by mosaics in front of decorated vitrines and hotels. Place Vendôme is lined with the world’s best jewelers and their glittering window displays. Every other establishment has someone to open the door for you or park your car. You can spend hours gazing at its haute couture shops or lingering over a meal at any of its chic eateries. After all that indulgence, the Tuileries gardens provide stately respite, while theaters compete for your applause. It's a neighborhood that draws admirers from around the world, all attracted to the luxe life in Paris.
How to get there
  • Palais Royal – Musée du Louvre • 3 min walk
  • Louvre – Rivoli • 5 min walk

  • Around the World in 80 Stays
    London, United Kingdom115 contributions
    The Most Visited Museum in the World
    Well 8 million visitors a year can’t be wrong! A visit to the Louvre is an absolute must if you visit Paris. It’s packed with 35,000 pieces of some of the world's best and most famous artwork such as Leonardo Da Vinci's Mona Lisa and Virgin of the Rocks. Not only famous for its priceless art, the Louvre also contains more than 380,000 objects including an impressive collection of sculptures and statues including the Venus de Milo. Ticket prices are very reasonable at €17 per adult, and children under 18 years go free! **Hot Tips: Book your tickets in advance, but even then, there’ll likely be a huge queue to get in. If the queues up top seem long, head into the shopping mall and locate the entry point on the lower ground floor as it’s often quicker. **Hot Tips: There is always a huge queue to see the Mona Lisa, so the best time to visit is just before closing time! For a full visual review of our trip to the ‘Louvre’, please click on the 'Around the World in 80 Stays' icon and follow the YouTube link to see a glossy film of the whole 'Louvre' experience plus many other films. Stephen C
Choppington, UK14 contributions
Louvre: A Masterpiece Marred by Queue Chaos
Nov 2024 • Couples
The Good:

* A Treasure Trove of Art: The Louvre is undoubtedly a masterpiece, housing countless iconic artworks and sculptures. The sheer scale and diversity of the collection is awe-inspiring.

* The Mona Lisa: Seeing this famous painting in person is a bucket-list experience. While the crowds can be overwhelming, the opportunity to witness this iconic artwork is truly special.

The Bad:

* Poor Queue Management: The organization of the queues is chaotic, with multiple lines for different visitor types. This can lead to long wait times, especially for those without pre-booked tickets or priority access.

* Crowded Conditions: The sheer number of visitors can make it difficult to fully appreciate the art, particularly around popular exhibits like the Mona Lisa.

Tips for Visitors:

* Book Tickets in Advance: This will significantly reduce your wait time and ensure a smoother entry.

* Arrive Early: If you don't have pre-booked tickets, aim to arrive as early as possible to minimize queue times.

* Be Patient: The crowds and long lines can be frustrating, but the rewards are worth it.

* Use the Louvre's App: The app provides helpful information, maps, and audio guides.

While the Louvre's art collection is truly exceptional, the poor queue management detracts from the overall experience. If you're planning a visit, be prepared for crowds and long wait times, but ultimately, the incredible art within will make it worthwhile.
Written November 2, 2024
